parts:
A coding agent created a git commit

Commit: d21d3ba

How do I push this to my remote repo?

If the commit `d21d3ba` exists in your **local** repo, you push it by pushing the **branch that contains it** to your remote.

### 1) Make sure you’re on the branch with that commit
```bash
git status
git log --oneline -5
```
If you’re not on the right branch, switch to it:
```bash
git switch <branch-name>
```

### 2) Push the branch to your remote
Most common case (remote is `origin`):
```bash
git push origin <branch-name>
```

If it’s a new local branch that doesn’t exist on the remote yet, set upstream:
```bash
git push -u origin <branch-name>
```

### 3) If you don’t know the branch name
Find which branch contains that commit:
```bash
git branch --contains d21d3ba
```
Then push that branch:
```bash
git push origin <that-branch>
```

### 4) If you’re in a detached HEAD state (common with agents/CI)
If `git status` shows “HEAD detached …”, create a branch at that commit and push it:
```bash
git switch -c agent-commit d21d3ba
git push -u origin agent-commit
```

### 5) Verify the remote and your authentication
List remotes:
```bash
git remote -v
```

If `origin` isn’t set:
```bash
git remote add origin <remote-url>
git push -u origin <branch-name>
```

If you tell me the output of `git status` and `git remote -v`, I can give the exact one-liner you should run.
